 "executive_summary": "This study presents crystal structures of HLA-A*2402-bound HIV-1 Nef134-10 peptide complexed with wild-type and escape-mutant TCRs, revealing how the virus evades CD8+ T-cell recognition through sequential mutations at positions 135 and 139. The Y135F mutation, though disrupting a key hydrogen bond to HLA, is functionally compensated by a newly formed interaction at residue 138, allowing the epitope to maintain its overall conformation while becoming poorly recognized by wild-type TCRs; conversely, the late-appearing F139L mutation represents a true escape variant that emerges in patients lacking the Y135F mutation. TCR clones from patients exposed to Y135F or capable of cross-recognizing both variants adopt distinct binding modes to accommodate the mutant peptide, indicating that structural TCR plasticity can partially overcome viral immune escape. These findings illustrate how HIV-1 selects for sequential epitope mutations under CTL pressure and explain the population-level dynamics of escape variant emergence during chronic HIV infection.",
